\begin{abstract}

{\textcolor{black} }{We consider the field theory of a superconductor with a topological axion term and construct its dual theories for both bulk and boundary at strong coupling. The theory describes, e.g., a conventional superconductor sandwiched between two topological insulators. The interacting topological states that emerge are classified by a $\mathbb{Z}_8$  invariant and the strong coupling boundary theory is shown to be purely topological. These topological states lack a non-interacting equivalent.  Due to the Witten effect, magnetic monopoles attain a fractional electric charge. This leads to an anomalous AC Josephson current generated by external magnetic fields. }

\end{abstract}


\maketitle


A plethora of topological states of matter have been identified and classified during the past 
decade~\cite{Hasan-Kane-RMP,Zhang-RMP-2011,Classif}. These include material realizations such as strong topological insulators (STI). Interestingly, the microscopic electronic structure of these materials can be very different. However, some properties of an STI, set by topology, are universal. A celebrated example is the bulk-boundary correspondence guaranteeing the presence of surface states that are protected by the bulk topology.
Another incarnation of this universality arises in the field-theoretical description of the electromagnetic response of STIs: it is governed by the canonical Maxwell Lagrangian supplemented by a topological term - the axion or $\theta$-term, 
$\sim\theta~{\bf E}\cdot{\bf B}$, which quantizes the electromagnetic response~\cite{Qi-2008}. 

{\textcolor{black} }{
Instead of an STI we consider a {\it superconductor} with a $\theta$-term and show that it is described by a compact Maxwell theory in 3+1 dimensions.   

Such an interacting field theory describes a superconducting slab sandwiched between two semi-infinite STIs (see Fig.~\ref{Fig:TI-SC-TI}a). As we will detail, here the STIs induce a $\theta$-term in the superconductor which couples to the electrodynamics of vortex lines. The corresponding Lagrangian has not been considered and represents a general field theory for (strongly) interacting topological states of matter.
}

{\textcolor{black} }{
It is well-known that {\it without} the topological axion term the compact Maxwell theory in 3+1 dimensions exhibits a confinement-deconfinement transition \cite{Guth}. This transition can be understood by exploiting the duality of the compact Maxwell theory to the non-compact U(1) abelian Higgs model \cite{Peskin}. In the dual Higgs model vortex lines  correspond to worldlines of magnetic monopoles in the original model.  Hence, the phase transition in the dual Higgs model corresponds to the confinement-deconfinement transition in the original compact U(1) Maxwell electrodynamics. 



We consider this duality in the presence of a topological axion term and explicitly construct the dual theories at the boundary. We demonstrate that due to the $\theta$-term the phase transition, that is discontinuous in the bulk, becomes critical at the boundary.  At the 
critical point, the effective bare coupling at the boundary diverges and the field theory becomes purely topological. A strongly interacting topological state having no non-interacting (or weakly interacting) equivalent then appears. We illustrate that the resulting topological states are classified by a $\mathbb{Z}_8$ index. We demonstrate that the emergence of a Witten effect \cite{Witten-effect}, which in the field theoretical description causes magnetic monopoles to attain a (fractional) electric charge leads to a {\it zero-bias Josephson current} generated by an external magnetic field. This signature of the Witten effect is predicted for fields perpendicular to superconducting slabs sandwiched between two STIs.

}



